WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.125 --> 00:00:03.485
Guillain-Barré syndrome, or GBS, is

2
00:00:03.484 --> 00:00:06.425
not a primary lung disease, but it can
quickly become

3
00:00:06.425 --> 00:00:07.824
a respiratory emergency.

4
00:00:08.465 --> 00:00:10.765
The key problem is neuromuscular weakness.

5
00:00:11.265 --> 00:00:14.984
The immune system attacks peripheral
nerves, often after a recent

6
00:00:14.984 --> 00:00:19.305
gastrointestinal or respiratory infection,
and this can cause ascending weakness

7
00:00:19.305 --> 00:00:21.004
that moves from the legs upward.

8
00:00:21.284 --> 00:00:25.364
For respiratory therapists, the concern is
what happens when that

9
00:00:25.364 --> 00:00:27.805
weakness reaches the muscles needed for
breathing, coughing,

10
00:00:28.745 --> 00:00:29.924
swallowing, and airway protection.

11
00:00:30.725 --> 00:00:33.384
The diaphragm, intercostal muscles,
accessory muscles,

12
00:00:33.544 --> 00:00:35.525
and bulbar muscles may all become
involved.

13
00:00:36.305 --> 00:00:39.345
When that happens, the patient may lose
ventilatory strength,

14
00:00:40.064 --> 00:00:42.325
develop a weak cough, retain secretions,

15
00:00:42.985 --> 00:00:45.485
aspirate, or progress toward respiratory
failure.

16
00:00:46.125 --> 00:00:48.625
A major board prep point is this.

17
00:00:49.025 --> 00:00:51.544
Do not rely on oxygen saturation alone.

18
00:00:52.104 --> 00:00:57.224
A patient with GBS may have a normal SpO2
while their respiratory mechanics are

19
00:00:57.224 --> 00:00:57.944
getting worse.

20
00:00:58.805 --> 00:01:00.884
That is why serial monitoring matters.

21
00:01:01.665 --> 00:01:05.565
RTs should trend vital capacity or forced
vital capacity, NIF

22
00:01:05.565 --> 00:01:08.705
or MIP, cough strength, secretion
clearance,

23
00:01:09.544 --> 00:01:11.845
respiratory pattern, fatigue, mental
status,

24
00:01:12.184 --> 00:01:14.205
and ABG or carbon dioxide trends.

25
00:01:14.964 --> 00:01:18.665
Red flags include rapidly falling vital
capacity, a weaker or

26
00:01:18.665 --> 00:01:21.665
less negative NIF, weak cough, pooling

27
00:01:21.665 --> 00:01:24.285
secretions, dysphagia, wet voice,

28
00:01:25.105 --> 00:01:28.845
rising PaCO2, falling pH, autonomic
instability,

29
00:01:29.824 --> 00:01:31.345
exhaustion, or altered mental status.

30
00:01:32.065 --> 00:01:36.245
These findings suggest the patient may be
losing ventilatory reserve or airway protection.

31
00:01:37.404 --> 00:01:40.805
Diagnostics may include lumbar puncture
findings, such as elevated protein

32
00:01:40.805 --> 00:01:45.165
with normal or low cell count, known as
albuminocytologic dissociation,

33
00:01:45.525 --> 00:01:49.264
and nerve conduction studies showing
demyelinating or axonal injury.

34
00:01:49.264 --> 00:01:53.565
But for the RT, the most important bedside
question is

35
00:01:53.565 --> 00:01:56.184
can this patient ventilate, protect the
airway,

36
00:01:56.184 --> 00:01:57.644
and clear secretions?

37
00:01:57.964 --> 00:02:02.025
Treatment may include IVIG or
plasmapheresis to address the immune process,

38
00:02:02.144 --> 00:02:05.565
but these treatments do not immediately
restore respiratory strength.

39
00:02:06.345 --> 00:02:08.485
Supportive respiratory care remains
critical.

40
00:02:09.524 --> 00:02:13.824
RT interventions may include frequent
respiratory mechanics checks, airway clearance,

41
00:02:14.485 --> 00:02:16.705
cough assist, suctioning, positioning,

42
00:02:17.404 --> 00:02:20.184
lung expansion support, ventilator
monitoring, and

43
00:02:20.184 --> 00:02:22.404
early communication with the team when
trends worsen.

44
00:02:22.744 --> 00:02:26.324
If the patient develops rising carbon
dioxide, fatigue,

45
00:02:26.925 --> 00:02:29.225
poor cough, bulbar weakness, or rapidly

46
00:02:29.225 --> 00:02:32.205
declining mechanics, escalation should
happen early.

47
00:02:33.065 --> 00:02:38.985
Waiting for severe desaturation is a
common mistake because oxygenation may stay acceptable until

48
00:02:38.985 --> 00:02:40.824
ventilatory failure is advanced.

49
00:02:41.505 --> 00:02:43.145
The clinical takeaway is simple.

50
00:02:43.964 --> 00:02:48.024
Guillain-Barre syndrome can quietly
progress from limb weakness to respiratory pump failure.

51
00:02:49.044 --> 00:02:53.404
RTs protect these patients by trending
mechanics, recognizing airway protection

52
00:02:53.404 --> 00:02:56.985
problems, supporting secretion clearance,
and escalating

53
00:02:56.985 --> 00:02:58.664
before respiratory collapse occurs.

